courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of this course students should be better able to:
- describe the central role of language in the creation and discovery of meaning;
- demonstrate a critical appreciation of the ways in which form, structure, and language shape meanings in literary texts;
- discuss the historical contexts of the globalization of English and their cultural consequences;
- synthesize information and ideas drawn from various sources, and evaluate critically opposing positions;
- describe how language and literature express individual and human values within an historical and sociocultural context;
- think imaginatively and analytically, and develop creative, ethical solutions to problems;
- express ideas with clarity, coherence, creativity, and fluency in both written and oral communication;
- use these new understandings as a basis for further studies in the humanities.

It is hoped that after taking this course students will be able to:

- read literary texts closely;
- have a basic understanding of the literary terms and concepts learned in the course;
- develop an enjoyment of literature which will continue beyond the classroom.

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:

- Closely read the literary text and the filmic/television text;

- Critically analyse the specificity of each medium;

- Explore the interaction of the literary text and its film/television adaptation;

- Engage with key issues in adaptation studies;

- Have a historical awareness of nineteenth-century literature and its relevance to the present.

Subject specific skills.
On successful completion of this course students will:
be able to understand key cultural theories;
have acquired historical and cultural literacy relating to literature and medicine;
have developed frameworks for understanding the societal role of the humanities.

Central academic skills.
On successful completion of this course students will have developed:
analytical skills in relation to visual and written texts;
organizational skills in the preparation of various review, commentary, and presentation assignments;
basic research skills using textual and visual sources;
basic writing skills in various formats (presentations, video commentaries, etc.).

Transferable skills.
On successful completion of this course students will have:
become confident in expressing their views, asking questions, and responding to others;
become more adept at giving presentations of their work.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

* describe theories and models of intercultural communication, cross-cultural/second language adjustment, identity reconstruction, and intercultural (communicative) competence;
* test these theories and models, using their own international/intercultural/second language experience;
* recognize and make an effort to avoid stereotyping/Otherization;
* employ a range of language- and culture-learning strategies while diversifying their social networks;
* articulate the intercultural skills and perspectives they have developed abroad;
* produce accounts of their international experience in English that demonstrate critical reflection and enhanced understanding of the impact of their own behavior and attitudes in intercultural interactions;
* assess their cultural self-awareness and intercultural communication skills, and set realistic goals for further enhancement of their second language proficiency, intercultural competence, and global-mindedness.

Students who complete this course will:

* Learn the key concepts, styles, and figures of modern and contemporary drama;
* Understand drama as both a literary text and a performance and apply this understanding in written and performed assignments;
* Analyse a representative selection of European and American plays from the late-nineteenth through to the twenty-first centuries;
* Reflect on the historical contexts from which drama emerges and the cultural questions it provokes;
* Develop skills of interpretation, communication, and collaboration.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
1) Understand the segmental aspects of English and apply the principles of the description and classification of speech sounds to English consonants and vowels;
2) Understand the role, use, and symbols of the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) and apply the IPA to the transcription of English words;
3) Understand the suprasegmental aspects of English, such as the English stress pattern and tone pattern and apply these aspects to the transcription of English words, phrases, and sentences;
4) Understand the differences between phonetics and phonology and explain basic phonological concepts;
5) Apply their understanding of basic phonological concepts to the development and analysis of different languages, including English.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

* read and analyze different types of environmental writing;
* understand genre, mode, audience, evidence, and visuals in relation to different types of environmental writing;
* demonstrate their understanding of environmental writing elements through the writing of 3 different pieces of environmental writing;
* have an enhanced awareness of global and local (Hong Kong) environmental issues;
* use technology to conduct research for environmental evidence;
* become more digitally literate through the reading, analysis, and writing of online environmental content.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

* understand the cultural, social, historical and linguistic development of Hong Kong English in relation to the major conceptual frameworks the course has explored;
* critically examine how language attitudes and standard language ideologies develop in different societies, and how gender and identity impact attitudes and ideologies across cultures;

* demonstrate an understanding of language attitudes and cultures through original research on the attitudes towards and status of Hong Kong English in Hong Kong society;
* define and give examples of different features of Hong Kong English;
* conduct original research on either written or spoken features of Hong Kong English;
* read and analyze research on Hong Kong English;
* use technology to conduct research on Hong Kong English;
* become more digitally literate through the reading, analysis, and writing of online Hong Kong English content*.*

Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
1) understand the scope of forensic linguistics as a sub-branch of applied linguistics;
2) identify different types of linguistic data that can be used as forensic evidence;
3) construct a basic linguistic profile of a text;
4) discuss the role and responsibilities of forensic linguists in legal investigations;
5) critically assess the strengths and limits of linguistic evidence in the legal process.

