courses.learning_outcomes:
Subject specific skills.

On successful completion of this course you will:

be able to identify and apply key linguistic and cultural theories;

have accumulated linguistic, historical and cultural knowledge relating to World Englishes in different societies and cultures;

have developed an applied understanding of theoretical frameworks for reading English language cultures generally.

Central academic skills.

On successful completion of this course you will have developed:

analytical skills pertinent to visual and written texts;

organizational skills in the preparation of various writing and presentation assignments;

basic research skills using textual and visual sources;

basic writing skills in standard academic formats (presentations, essays).

Transferable skills.

On successful completion of this course you will have:

become confident in expressing your views, asking questions, and responding to others, even in large groups;

become more professional in delivering formal presentations of your work.

By the end of this course, you will be able to:

• appreciate the scale and diversity of writing in English;
• recognize the significance of cross-cultural exchange in contemporary writing in English;
• draw on key aspects of postcolonial literary theory and diaspora studies in order to productively explore world literatures in English;
• produce a well-reasoned essay.

By the end of the course you should be able to:

‧ describe the relationship between language, communication, and culture;
‧ explain how culture influences your own life (e.g., values, beliefs, communication style);
‧ discuss the nature of cultural differences and identify productive, mindful ways to meet the challenges of intercultural communication;
‧ recognize diverse ways of communicating in different cultural situations;
‧ assess your cultural self-awareness and communication style and set realistic goals to enhance your intercultural communicative competence (e.g., ability to communicate effectively with people from other cultures) and appreciation of other cultures;
‧ work effectively in a group to produce a written report and oral presentation that reflect critical thought about intercultural communication theories/practice and demonstrate respect for other ‘ways of being’.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

- be aware of the internal structure of words and of the systematic relationships among words in English;
- possess a basic understanding of the history of English and the historical development of its vocabulary;
- perform morphological, phonological and semantic analyses of words;
- understand in what ways words are subject to variation and change;
- grasp the semantic and syntactic knowledge of various kinds of figurative language in English such as idioms and phrasal verbs;
- be familiar with the nature of L2 vocabulary acquisition and its subsequent vocabulary learning strategies; and

- practise lexical knowledge in everyday language use.

Students are expected to

- Have a deeper understanding of the Romantic period;
- Grasp the key features of each of these major Romantic poets;
- Have an awareness of the sources and legacy of Romantic tradition;
- Enjoy reading poetry and to read it critically.

