• introduces themes and contexts for reading literature, and understanding culture more generally;
• provides advanced vocabulary and methods for further study in culture;
• develops a range of study skills relevant to further study in the department and undergraduate studies in general.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
Evaluate the literary contributions of Asian American/Canadian writers, and appreciate/recognize their achievements;
Identify the major issues represented in Asian American/Canadian literatures, and elucidate them in light of their social, historical and cultural contexts;
Analyze the literary elements of a work written by an Asian American/Canadian author, and explain its distinctive features in terms of style, characterization and narrative technique.

At the end of the course, it is expected that students will:
1. have in-depth knowledge of, and understand the relationships between, the lives, literary themes and methods of some major authors in the Victorian period;
2. be able to compare the different approaches and themes in literature by different Victorian authors;
3. recognize important aspects of Victorian literature as continuations of, or distinct from, other literary periods;
4. be able to analyze Victorian literature through the lens of the historical issues and social debates in this period;
5. be able to describe how literary themes and methods changed across the Victorian period with the change of socio-political conditions and artistic methods;
6. be able to critically reflect on choices made in the representation of Victorian literature by different media, such as film and art.

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:

- Closely read literary texts of ekphrasis;

- Have an awareness of the historical context of ekphrastic texts;

- Critically analyse the respective features of verbal and visual mediums;

- Explore the interaction between the verbal and visual mediums;

- Engage with important ideas and concepts in ekphrastic studies.

This course will require you to:
• demonstrate your understanding of (1) the dynamic notion of text, (2) various ways to analyze spoken and written discourse, and (3) ways to transfer and apply understanding about texts to other situations (especially teaching and learning) in class discussions and fieldwork research;
• use and explain key discourse analysis concepts and terms appropriately;
• identify, describe/explain, and apply key discourse analysis theories, approaches, and analysts;
• analyze the rhetorical and syntactic features of an essay (text as written discourse) resulting in a stylistic analysis report;
• apply cohesion principles in an advertisement (text as spoken and written); this project requires you to (1) create a written script for an ad; (2) produce/act in the video clip of the ad; (3) design and produce a print ad; and (4) evaluate the video and print ad in terms of their rhetorical and linguistic elements;
• research and complete a conversational analysis of selected pragmatic elements in a film (text as talk); this project requires you to observe and transcribe verbal/non-verbal behaviors in order to identify, explain, and interpret speech act principles and applications;
• gain experience in working and communicating in teams to establish aims, problem solve, develop strategies, delegate responsibilities, negotiate schedules and deadlines, take on varying collaborative roles (as leaders and group members), as well as compose and produce effective discourse analysis documents;
• prepare and participate in small group research conferences with your teacher; and
• recognize, understand, and communicate to others how discourse works in the language used in different situations (e.g., education, government, business, social, and personal) around you, especially in Hong Kong (i.e., newspapers, magazines, television, radio, Internet, CUHK functions, etc.).

This course will require you to:
‧ demonstrate your understanding of (1) the major approaches to gender and language; (2) various ways men and women as well as same-sex speakers develop and use language differently in a variety of settings and situations, and (3) importance of the relationship between linguistic and social variables in the study of gender and language;
‧ use and explain key concepts and terms appropriately;
‧ identify, describe/explain, and apply key sociolinguistic theories, approaches, and researchers;
‧ observe, record, and analyze the verbal and non-verbal behaviors of same-sex and mixed-sex pairs, resulting in a data-driven fieldwork report;
‧ apply sociolinguistic and discourse analysis knowledge to analyze same-sex and mixed-sex verbal and non-verbal behaviors on such areas as “women’s” language, taboo language, or politeness;
‧ read, evaluate, and write a review of a book on gender and language research;
‧ gain experience in working and communicating in teams to establish aims, problem solve, develop strategies, delegate responsibilities, negotiate schedules and deadlines, take on varying collaborative roles (as leaders and group members), as well as compose and produce effective fieldwork reports and academic essays;
‧ prepare and participate in small group research conferences with your teacher; and
‧ recognize, understand, and communicate to others how gender and language may influence language use in different situations and among different speakers (e.g., public and private discourse, interpersonal vs. group discourse, dominant-subordinate discourse at home or in the workplace, couple talk, children at play interaction, mixed talk in female/male dominated professions, etc.) around you, especially in Hong Kong.

By the end of the course students should be able to:
• assess their international/reentry experiences and articulate how it has affected their sense of self /worldview;
• describe theories and models of culture shock, transitions, re-entry, identity reconstruction, intercultural (communicative) competence, and responsible global, intercultural citizenship;
• test these theories and models, using their own international/intercultural experiences, case studies, and narratives found in literature, media, interviews, and research reports;
• assess their cultural self-awareness and communication style and set realistic goals to enhance their intercultural communicative competence (e.g., ability to communicate effectively with people from other cultures) and global competency;
• integrate their international/intercultural experiences into their daily life/plans for the future (e.g., career goals, further studies/travel/volunteering abroad);
• express their ideas more clearly in English in both written and oral form (e.g., reflective narratives/blogs, poems, essays, online discussions, group oral presentation/sharing session with future exchange students).

By the end of this course, students are expected to be able to...

* Tell the differences between bottom-up linguistic processing and top-down conceptual processing in reading comprehension;
* Explain the relative weight of background knowledge and L2 linguistic knowledge in L2 reading comprehension;
* Engage more actively in task-based and technology-mediated English reading;
* Utilize graded readers more efficiently in developing L2 reading ability; and
* Develop lesson plans or syllabi that can facilitate both L2 reading ability and L2 competence.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
• Discuss the nature and patterns of child first language phonological acquisition and apply their knowledge to the analysis of authentic child language data;
• Discuss the nature and patterns of child and adult second language phonological acquisition and apply their knowledge to the analysis of authentic second language data;
• Understand the social factors involved in the acquisition and use of second language phonology;
• Explain the role of accent in identity and intelligibility and apply this knowledge to the development of questionnaire/surveys to elicit authentic data on accent;
• Discuss the features and role of Hong Kong English;
• Collect and analyze authentic phonological data;
• Collect and analyze quantitative and qualitative social factors data;
• Design and carry out a phonological research project.

courses.course_syllabus:
• The phonological system of English as well as other languages;
• The International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) and its usage in teaching and conducting research;
• The main issues involved in the acquisition of a first and second language phonology, including linguistic factors (e.g., transfer, markedness) and social factors (e.g., social identity, gender, L1/L2 use, motivation);
• The definition(s) of accent and how accent relates to identity and intelligibility as well as stereotyping;
• The features of Hong Kong English.

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students are expected to:
• develop a conceptual and functional understanding of AI;
• be able to make use of AI-based techniques/applications to explore key issues related to human language,
especially those related to English;
• be able to think critically and creatively about the pros and cons of individual AI-based techniques/applications;
and
• develop/improve their critical thinking skills while engaging in self-reflections and discussions on important
issues of their interest.

Expected student learning outcomes from this course are as follows:

* Students will develop a conceptual and functional understanding of AI;
* Students will operate a variety of AI-based applications (and programming codes in Python) and examine their features to evaluate their effectiveness in achieving specific purposes;
* Students will be able to apply AI technologies to identify/explore key problems/solutions in their major field;

Students will be able to create a website where diverse AI techniques are used for investigating the problems/solutions of their choice.

On completion of the course, students will have been able to:

• define the scope of the emerging field of ‘Internet Linguistics’;

• identify and analyze linguistic features that are specific to the context of digital communication;

• critically examine the possible impact of new communication media on language use;

• analyze online texts by applying concepts and theories in linguistics.

