courses.learning_outcomes:
The course will:
- deepen students’ knowledge and critical understanding of the complex relationship between language policy, culture, and identity in a diverse range of socio-political contexts in Asia (e.g., Hong Kong, Malaysia, Singapore, Japan, India, Brunei Darussalam, North and South Korea, Pakistan, Vietnam, Cambodia, China, Nepal);
- enhance their understanding of the impact of globalization, glocalization, and internationalization on language policies, local cultures, and identities;
- enhance their competence and confidence in both written and oral English;
- provide the opportunity for students to work collaboratively in small groups to investigate language planning and policy issues in an Asian setting of their choice;
- require groups to produce a coherent, substantive written report and oral presentation based on their research findings;
- help students polish their professional presentation skills in a formal conference setting.

On completion of the course, students should be able to:
♦ understand the nature and linguistic features of written communication on the Internet;
♦ discuss the impact of new communication technologies on language;
♦ analyze online texts by applying concepts and theories in linguistics.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

• recognize and identify the concept of utopia in science fiction writing;
• discriminate between the various representations of utopia in science fiction literature;
• analyze the ways in which the notion of utopia has been drawn on by writers to critique contemporary society;
• draw on the theoretical and critical material discussed in this course in order to produce both a formal essay and an original short story, which have as their focus the concept of utopia.

In this course, students will:

* investigate texts, topics, and issues within American literature;
* understand the social, cultural, and political conditions surrounding the writing and reception of American literature;

* evaluate concepts and connect them across a range of texts, including novels, drama, films, and poetry;

* communicate ideas effectively in collaborative discussions and written tasks;
* apply critical thinking and research skills in oral presentations and written assignments;
* formulate independent research questions and develop them in a final essay.

