After this course, students should be better able to:
• discuss the nature and scope of intercultural communication theory and practice;
• identify the role of intercultural communication in the wider context of applied linguistics;
• explain and use related key concepts and terms appropriately;
• assess theories and key research findings in intercultural communication;
• read primary sources critically and effectively;
• describe and assess research techniques used in intercultural communication research;
• describe the nature of cultural differences and assess their impact on linguistic and nonverbal communication in intercultural interactions in Hong Kong and elsewhere;
• work individually (and collaboratively) to produce oral and written work that is clear, concise, and coherent.

Specific student learning outcomes expected from this course are:

• Students will develop a conceptual and functional understanding of NLP;
• Students will be able to apply NLP techniques to explore basic issues in (applied) linguistics;
• Students will be able to think critically and creatively about the pros and cons of individual NLP techniques.

By the end of the course, students should:
• better understand the role of research in applied English linguistics;
• be more familiar with current applied linguistics research, and the different paradigms of inquiry, including the instruments/ approaches, modes of analysis, and major findings;
• be aware of the principles behind conducting sound applied linguistics research;
• understand and be able to explain the fundamental concepts and specific procedures involved in the conduct of applied linguistics research;
• be able to design a coherent, feasible proposal in the field of applied English linguistics.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the key contexts and Issues in ESP, and how they are related to developments in English language teaching, and more broadly, to applied linguistics research;
• review current research, exploring functional description of variation in academic and professional discourses and genres, and use insights from analysis as input to the development of ESP materials;
• identify analytical insights from current research in discourse and genre studies relevant to the development, design and teaching of English for academic and professional communication programmes; and,
• analyse specific instances of academic and professional ESP course materials currently in use, particularly focusing on authenticity in the selection of input, opportunities available for exploiting new technology and digital media, and above-all, the use of appropriate ESP methodology in teaching, learning and evaluating interdiscursive performance in specialised contexts.

Students will be able to:
• grasp a summary of both theoretical and practical ideas that SLT professionals, scholars and researchers have produced;
• provoke careful thinking about L2 teaching issues via processes such as critical analysis of teaching materials, comparison of different techniques, problem-solving and debate on controversial topics; and
• to examine pedagogical problems and adapt tasks to enhance teaching effectiveness;
• formulate their own L2 teaching theories and practically incorporate what they have theorized for themselves into their own L2 classroom.

