After taking the course, students should:

- Be familiar with the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) and its usage in teaching and conducting research

- Understand the main issues involved in the acquisition of an L2 phonology, including linguistics and social factors;
- Be aware of research on training and classroom practices as well as research on various linguistic and social factors;
- Be able to analyze the pronunciation phenomena of learners and apply phonological acquisition theories to explain the phenomena;
- Be able to apply teaching theories and acquisition theories to develop pronunciation teaching plans and materials for learners.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

i. demonstrate an in-depth understanding of the key concerns, aims, theoretical assumptions, theories and methodologies employed in the CL enterprise;
ii. manifest an ability to critically evaluate various theories in the field;
iii. deploy a range of complex principles and analytic methods common in the enterprise;
iv. apply the theoretical assumptions pertaining to human cognitive structure, organization and ability to the practical pedagogy in L2 classroom; and

v. be willing to experiment with the CL approach to second language teaching.

After completing this project-based course, students will be able to:
1) gain considerably in-depth knowledge in a chosen area of study;
2) develop academic skills in carrying out an independent research project in Applied Linguistics;
3) select and critically review relevant literature on the chosen topic of research;
4) apply relevant theoretical concepts and research methods for data collection and analysis;
5) communicate their research findings effectively through an oral presentation and a substantial piece of academic writing.

By the end of this course, students are expected to be able to...

* Explain the underlying cognitive processes involved in reading in English as a second language;
* Review research findings on the second language reading from a critical perspective;
* Analyze existing English reading instructional materials (graded readers, reading comprehension tasks, lesson plans, and syllabus) based on theories of second language reading; and
* Construct effective second language reading teaching materials and syllabus.

